The '''Consortium of Liberal Arts Colleges''' ('''CLAC''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberalarts.org/|title=Reach out. Connect. Collaborate. - Consortium of Liberal Arts Colleges|website=Consortium of Liberal Arts Colleges|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-26}}</ref> is a [[nonprofit]] organization of 70 American [[liberal arts colleges]] which formed in 1984 under the leadership of [[Oberlin College]]'s president [[S. Frederick Starr]].<ref>Victor E. Ferrall, Jr., ''Liberal Arts at the Brink'' ([[Harvard University Press]], 2011), {{ISBN|978-0674049727}}, p. 86. [https://books.google.com/books?id=cJ1s33h1gRoC&lpg=PA86&dq=%22Consortium%20of%20Liberal%20Arts%20Colleges%22%20oberlin&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=%22Consortium%20of%20Liberal%20Arts%20Colleges%22%20oberlin&f=false Excerpts available] at [[Google Books]].</ref> CLAC brings together the IT professionals from its member colleges and universities to help those institutions make the best use of technology to enrich students’ learning, facilitate teaching and research, and to support the business of the higher education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberalarts.org/|title=Reach out. Connect. Collaborate. - Consortium of Liberal Arts Colleges|website=Consortium of Liberal Arts Colleges|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-26}}</ref> CLAC has been supporting collaboration, knowledge sharing, professional growth of its IT members, and advocacy for the liberal arts at the national level for more three decades.
The organization will celebrate its 20th Annual Conference in 2018.
