[[File:CMOC Treasures of Ancient China exhibit - calligraphy brush with dragon design.jpg|thumb|Ink brush with golden dragon design, used by the [[Wanli Emperor]] (1563-1620).]] '''Ink brushes''' ({{Zh|t=毛筆|s=毛笔|p=máo bǐ}}; {{lang-ja|筆|fude}}; {{lang-ko|붓/筆}}) are used in [[Chinese calligraphy]] as well as [[Japanese calligraphy]] and [[Korean calligraphy]] which have a root of Chinese calligraphy. They are also used in [[Chinese painting]] and other [[brush painting]] styles. The brush was invented in China around 300 B.C.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ong|first=Siew Chey|title=China condensed: 5000 years of history & culture|year=2005|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|location=Singapore|isbn=978-981-261-067-6|pages=161|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bt7q8hfiZ4gC}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Women of China, Issues 1-6|year=1995|publisher=Foreign Language Press|pages=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nJWyAAAAIAAJ}}</ref> Together with the [[inkstone]], [[inkstick]] and [[Xuan paper]], these four writing implements form the [[Four Treasures of the Study]].
==Types== [[File:Upper Lascar Row, Hong Kong (2051987459).jpg|thumb|upright|Ink brushes of various size and material for sale]] Brushes differ greatly in terms of size, texture, material, and cost. The brush hair chosen depends on one's needs at the moment; certain kinds of brushes are more suited to certain [[East asian script styles |script styles ]] and individuals than others. * '''Handle''': usually of bamboo, exotic brushes may instead use such materials as gold, silver, jade, ivory, [[red sandalwood]] or [[spotted bamboo]]. * '''Hair source''': normally the brush is made from goat, [[Siberian weasel]] (ch: 黄鼠狼 huángshǔláng, yellow-rat-wolf), pig, mouse, [[domestic buffalo|buffalo]], wolf, or rabbit hair, while exotic ones can be made from tiger, [[fowl]], deer, and even human hair (from a baby's first haircut, said to bring good fortune while taking the [[imperial examination]]s). * '''Hair texture''': soft (ch: 軟毫 ruǎnháo), mixed (ch: 兼毫 jiānháo), or hard (ch: 硬毫 yìngháo) hair. *'''Hair size''': generally classified as either big (ch: 大楷 dàkǎi, ja: 大筆 oofude), medium (ch: 中楷 zhōngkǎi, ja: 中筆 chufude), or small (ch: 小楷 xiǎokǎi, ja: 小筆 kofude)<ref>{{cite book |first =莫山 |last =榊 |title =文房四宝 筆の話 |date =1981-05-30 |publisher =角川書店 |edition =1 |page =202}}</ref>; most calligraphy is written with a medium-sized brush. The smallest brushes are used for very small pieces and for fashioning designs for seals. While medium size brushes are the most widely used, wielded by a skilled artist a medium brush can produce a variety of thicknesses of line from very thin to fairly thick. The largest brushes are used only for very large pieces. *'''Hair length''': generally classified by hair length for thickness of handle as either long (ja: 長鋒 chouhou), medium (ja: 中鋒 chuhou), short (ja: 短鋒 tannhou); most calligraphy is written with a medium-length hair brush. The long hair brush are more keep to hold a ink than the short hair brushes as their length. So, it used for continuous long stroke line scripting such as Japanese traditional ''hiragana'' style by ''rennmen''( ja: 連綿 ). The hair of long hair brushes are tend to made by hard texture hair to keep their hair form, but there is a not one. Japanese very long and slender hair brushes called ''menso''-burushes（ ja: 面相筆 ） are used for detail painting.<ref>{{cite book |first =久夫 |last =堀 |title =書筆使いこなしハンドブック |date =2001-03-16 |publisher =可成屋 |edition =1 |isbn =4-8393-8721-4 |page =128}}</ref>
Synthetic hair is not traditionally used. Prices vary greatly depending on the quality of the brush; cheap brushes cost less than one US dollar while expensive brushes can cost more than a thousand dollars. Currently, the finest brushes are made in the town of [[Shanlian]], in the [[Nanxun District]], [[prefecture-level city]] of [[Huzhou]], of [[Zhejiang]] province.
==History== [[File:Pinceaux chinois.jpg|thumb|Brushes of various sizes and types of hair, including one of chicken feathers at the top]] {{Expand section|date=June 2008}} The earliest intact ink brush was found in 1954 in the tomb of a [[Chu (state)|Chu]] citizen from the [[Warring States period]] (475-221 [[Common Era|BCE]]) located in an archaeological dig site ''Zuo Gong Shan 15'' near [[Changsha]] (長沙). The primitive version of an ink brush found had a wooden stalk and a bamboo tube securing the bundle of hair to the stalk. Legend wrongly credits the invention of the ink brush to the later [[Qin dynasty|Qin]] general [[Meng Tian]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}
Traces of the writing brush, however, were discovered on the Shang jades, and were suggested to be the grounds of the oracle bone inscriptions.<ref>Cambridge History of Ancient China, 1999:108</ref>
==Fudepen== {{see also|Fudepen}}
The '''Fudepen''', also known as a "Brush Pen", is a modern Japanese invention analogous to a [[Fountain pen]]. Today, Japanese companies such as [[Pentel]] and [[Sakura Color Products Corporation]] manufacture pens with tips resembling those of a small ink brush. These brush pens work almost identically to small ink brushes and can be used for most of the same purposes.
